# TDD Checkpoint Audit Requirements

At each TDD checkpoint, before advancing to the next phase, audit **all 8 personas** below. For each category, cite the specific test(s) that satisfy it or write them if missing. Do not advance past a checkpoint until all categories are satisfied.

## 1. QE -- "Can we ship this with confidence?"
- Every new public function/method has at least one test traceable to a requirement
- For every happy-path test there is a corresponding error-path/rejection test
- No test anti-patterns: fixed sleeps, tautological assertions, shared mutable state, implementation-coupled assertions
- Every bug fix has a regression test; every race fix has a `-race` stress test

## 2. Prod Security -- "Can an attacker exploit this?"
- Every external string input (IDs, names, messages) has a test with: empty, max-length+1, invalid charset (e.g. `"../../etc/passwd"`), Unicode edge cases
- Secrets excluded from logs, metrics labels, and truncated tool responses
- RBAC verbs scoped to minimum; impersonation justified in ADR with compensating controls
- CI deps pinned to immutable refs (SHA); `govulncheck` clean

## 3. Product -- "Does this deliver what was promised?"
- Every acceptance criterion from the linked issue has a corresponding test or code path
- No silent breaking changes to API contracts, CRD schemas, or event formats
- No zombie code; deprecated features have notices before removal
- User-facing errors are actionable with no internal IDs or stack traces

## 4. UX -- "Is this intuitive to consume?"
- Endpoints, events, schemas documented and consistent with project conventions
- Naming follows conventions (snake_case JSON, camelCase Go, kebab-case K8s)
- Error responses include machine-readable code, human message, and retry context
- SSE streams have coherent lifecycle (start, progress, done, heartbeat, retry)

## 5. Architecture -- "Does this fit the system?"
- No circular deps; `internal/` never imports `cmd/`
- Interfaces at package boundaries; no concrete cross-package types where interfaces suffice
- CRD fields additive-only with defaults; implementation matches `docs/adr/`
- No test helpers or debug symbols exported from production packages

## 6. SRE/Ops -- "Can we run this in production?"
- For every metric defined, a test calls the production path and asserts the metric changed
- Error logs include structured context (resource name, namespace, phase) for SRE diagnosis
- Every map/slice/cache that grows with usage has a test running 50+ lifecycle cycles asserting bounded size
- Every method behind a mutex has a test with 10+ goroutines under `-race`
- External calls have timeouts, circuit breakers, fallbacks; readiness checks reflect real health

## 7. Release / Change Mgmt -- "Can we roll this out and back safely?"
- No irreversible migrations; CRD changes are additive-only
- High-risk behavior gated behind feature flags where appropriate
- User-visible changes documented; deployment ordering constraints noted

## 8. FedRAMP -- "Does this satisfy NIST 800-53?"
- AU-2/AU-12: security events (auth, session lifecycle, access denial) emit audit events
- AC-3/AC-6: RBAC least-privilege; impersonation documented in ADR
- IA-5: JWKS rotation with max cache age; fail-open justified in ADR
- SC-4/SC-28: PII classified per ADR-017; excluded from logs and metrics
- SI-10: external inputs sanitized per spec (RFC 1123, JWT claims, SSE fields)
